NEWS  
The General Coordinator of the response to the Ebola virus disease epidemic intervenes at the 28th ethics day in Kinshasa 
 • The general coordinator of the response to the Ebola virus disease epidemic, Prof. Steve Ahuka Mundeke, intervened this Saturday, January 04, 2020 at the twenty-eighth ethics day of Kinshasa organized by the urban council of the Order of physicians (CUOM) under the theme "Medical ethics and ethics, the foundation of practice the art of healing” in the Agora Amphitheater of the Bel Campus University in Kinshasa; 
• For Prof. Ahuka, there is a link between managing the epidemic and ethics in medical practice. The Ebola crisis, he said, concerns all health personnel, particularly doctors, recalling that doctors must intervene in this crisis while respecting the ethics as intended by this day; 
• "There are many aspects of deontology and ethics in medical practice and in the management of Ebola. Lack of hospital hygiene is one of the major factors in the spread of the disease. To this is added the lack of prevention and control of infection in Congolese hospitals. This is an important element of which doctors must be aware, "said the general coordinator of the response during the 28th ethics day in Kinshasa; 
• The intervention of the general coordinator of the response to the Ebola virus disease epidemic at these meetings focused on the communication on the current situation of the Ebola virus disease epidemic; 
• This day ended with the presentation of a diploma of merit to a few doctors and pharmacists for their distinction and commitment to their profession. The diploma of Professor Jean-Jacques Muyembe Ntamfum was symbolically awarded to Prof. Ahuka. 
